ish decision—completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a performance/latency requirement that depends on real model call times. MOCK-MISS: Integration with mocked classifiers returning instantly might show 50ms pipeline overhead and pass, but with real models (10–30s total latency) would fail. Integration testing hides the real bottleneck: actual model inference latency. REAL-INFRA: Must measure latency with real subprocess/API calls to models. System-level testing with actual model processes or realistic network calls is the boundary where latency becomes measurable.","test_description":"System test with real vision and NLP models. Submit an image + text post to the live pipeline, measure end-to-end elapsed time from submission to completion, repeat 5+ times with different images, verify latency does not exceed 5 seconds in any run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Performance cannot be verified without real model latencies; mocked instant classifiers would always pass regardless of actual performance.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure to catch is a pipeline error-handling logic bug: when the vision model fails, the post is auto-approved instead of queued. MOCK-MISS: This is false—mocking the classifier to raise an exception fully tests the error path. We're testing whether the pipeline correctly implements the error-handling rule (queue on failure), not testing whether the real model actually fails. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking an exception is representative of model unavailability; it correctly exercises the error path. Integration is sufficient.","test_description":"Integration test with mocked exception. Mock the vision model to raise a connection timeout